Preface

\(\quad\) The intention of our project here is to be able to compare the runtimes (in seconds) of both K-means and Complete Linkage Clustering across R, SAS, and Python.

Big-O-Notation

\(\quad\) We now introduce the abridged explanation of the concept of Big O Notation, which is widely used notation in Computer Science in describing performance and complexity of a given algorithm. Written as \(O()\), the complexity and thus runtime of an algorithm scales with the terms inside the parentheses. For example, an algorithm that runs with a Big O notation with \(O(n^2)\) would theoretically indicate that the algorithm performance directly scales proportionally to the square of the input size of the dataset. Thus \(O(n^2)\) algorithms will struggle the extensively larger your input dataset is.

\(\quad\) Theoretical Remark: Research on K-Means algorithm shows that the Big O notation is \(O(tkn)\), where \(n\) is the number of objects and \(k\) is the number of clusters and \(t\) is the number of iterations until convergence. Based on this, it would indicate that if we continued to increase the number of clusters beyond 6 to a very large number then eventually we will see longer runtimes. Since our number of observations and range of tested clusters is quite small (~1600 obs and 2-6 clusters), we could not see much difference. Similarly, the algorithm complexity is directly proportional directly to the size of the number of iterations and the number of observations.

\(\quad\) Similarly, research on agglomerative hierarchical clustering methods shows many methods to be \(O(n^3)\), or \(O(n^2)\) in some more efficient implementations at best. This would mean that the complexity and performance-intensity of the algorithm to be directly proportional to the cube of the size of the input, an extremely poor performing algorithm especially at large datasets. Thus if we were to consult a larger dataset (~100000+ observations), then it would take a very long time and slowly generate the output from the agglomerative clustering method.

K-means performance

\(\quad\) Here we will create the function k_means_time() that will track how long the kmeans function takes to perform across various K and Iterations values.

Below is an example of how to identify the timing of the algorithm:

 round(mean(microbenchmark(kmeans(wine, centers = 4, nstart = 1, iter.max = 10))$time*1e-9), 4)
## [1] 0.0018
k_means_time <- function(k, iterations){
  
results <- mat.or.vec(k-1, iterations)

for(i in 2:(k-1)){
  for(j in 1:iterations){
results[i,j] <- round(mean(microbenchmark(kmeans(wine, centers = i, nstart = 1, iter.max = j))$time*1e-9), 4)
                        }
}

return(data.frame(results)%>%
       magrittr::set_colnames(paste("Iter # ", 1:iterations))%>%
       magrittr::set_rownames(paste("K = ", 2:k))
       )

}

Python

Import/Clean data

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.cluster import *
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import time


wine = pd.read_csv('winequality-red.csv')
wine_y = wine.quality
wine_x = wine.drop('quality',1)

K-means/Complete Linkage Performance

\(\quad\) We will use time.clock to measure the runtime of different clusters. On Unix, time.clock returns the current processor time expressed in seconds, and on Windows, it returns the wall-clock time expressed in seconds elapsed since the first call to this function.

cluster_time_kmeans = np.zeros(5)
cluster_time_Hierarchical = np.zeros(5)

for k in range(2,7):
    start = time.clock()
    cluster_k = KMeans(n_clusters = k).fit(wine_x)
    end = time.clock()
    cluster_time_kmeans[k-2] = end-start
    start = time.clock()
    cluster_k = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = k,linkage = 'average').fit(wine_x)
    end = time.clock()
    cluster_time_Hierarchical[k-2] = end-start

cluster_time = pd.DataFrame({'Cluster_number': np.arange(2,7),'Kmeans':cluster_time_kmeans,'Hierarchical':cluster_time_Hierarchical})
cluster_time

Comments: Following is a plot to show our cluster results, and I choose k=3. Here I reduced the dimensions into 2 using PCA methods, and then make a scatter plot grouped by the three labels.

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA as sklearnPCA
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
pca = sklearnPCA(n_components=2) #2-dimensional PCA
kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=3)
kmeansoutput=kmeans.fit(wine_x)
transformed = pd.DataFrame(pca.fit_transform(wine_x),index = kmeansoutput.labels_)

plt.scatter(transformed.loc[0][0], transformed.loc[0][1], label='Class 1', c='red')
plt.scatter(transformed.loc[1][0], transformed.loc[1][1], label='Class 2', c='blue')
plt.scatter(transformed.loc[2][0], transformed.loc[2][1], label='Class 3', c='lightgreen')

plt.legend()
plt.title('scatter plot for kmeans with 3 clusters')
plt.show()

`

Remarks

\(\quad\) For Kmeans and Hierarchical cluster method respectively, runtime is not strictly depend on the cluster number. And for all cluster number, Kmeans runs a little faster than Hierarchical cluster.

Conclusion

\(\quad\) This concludes the tutorial in R, SAS, and Python on how to compute and compare algorithm execution times with different parameterizations of the k-means and complete linkage algorithms. Self-experimentation can be done to explore execution times, especially with extremely large datasets where memory and computational constraints are more relevant. Overall it is evident that k-means can be applied in simpler contexts with fast execution times, but complete linkage is a much more comprehensive algorithm at the cost of computational efficiency and execution time; these differences are especially exaggerated with larger and larger datasets.
